      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "4a1c3df1edd10690",
        "text": "This one forgoes growth and focuses on continuance. What is first noticeable about it is the border. The closed mass establishes itself. It creates its place by limiting itself; the space it will fill is assigned to it. It is comparable to a vessel into which one pours liquid; it is known how much liquid goes into it. The accesses to the space are counted, one cannot enter in every way. The boundary is respected. It may be made of stone, of solid masonry. Perhaps a special act of admission is required; perhaps one has to pay a certain fee to enter. Once the space is crowded enough, no one is allowed in. Even if it overflows, there still remains as the main thing the dense mass in the closed room, to which the outsiders do not seriously belong."
      },
      "after": "fd922f6d9f146768",
      "attribution": {
        "page": "Masse und Macht"
      },
      "date": 1698181640570
